00:33:46.080 --> 00:33:49.080
AUDIENCE: You say it's important
to get a grip of numbers,

00:33:49.080 --> 00:33:52.450
and understand and put them
into relation, big numbers

00:33:52.450 --> 00:33:54.540
especially.

00:33:54.540 --> 00:33:57.690
How do you suggest
we help people

00:33:57.690 --> 00:34:03.330
do that, because lots of
people, probably all of us,

00:34:03.330 --> 00:34:05.947
struggle with very big numbers
and putting them in relations.

00:34:05.947 --> 00:34:07.530
ANDREW ELLIOTT: I
mean, I talk through

00:34:07.530 --> 00:34:09.420
in the book various techniques.

00:34:09.420 --> 00:34:12.330
The top one there, landmark
numbers, is one that I think

00:34:12.330 --> 00:34:13.419
is very important.

00:34:13.419 --> 00:34:15.210
What I mean by landmark
number is something

00:34:15.210 --> 00:34:17.856
that sticks in your brain.

00:34:17.856 --> 00:34:19.230
You don't set out
to memorize it,

00:34:19.230 --> 00:34:21.940
but it sticks in your
brain as a reference point.

00:34:21.940 --> 00:34:24.510
And I hope that all
of you will leave

00:34:24.510 --> 00:34:29.382
knowing that 40,000 kilometers
is the length of the equator.

00:34:29.382 --> 00:34:30.840
And that can be a
reference number.

00:34:30.840 --> 00:34:34.880
So when you see that, you may--

00:34:34.880 --> 00:34:36.480
Australia is 1/10 of that.

00:34:36.480 --> 00:34:39.340
Africa north to south
is one fifth of that.

00:34:39.340 --> 00:34:41.440
It becomes something
that's in your head that

00:34:41.440 --> 00:34:46.730
is a ready reference
for you to relate to.

00:34:46.730 --> 00:34:50.429
And the 7 and 1/2 billion
people in the world.

00:34:50.429 --> 00:34:54.919
These are numbers which, if
you have them ready to hand,

00:34:54.919 --> 00:34:56.460
they help you to
make these yardstick

00:34:56.460 --> 00:34:58.510
comparisons against things
that you hear about.

00:34:58.510 --> 00:34:59.520
And it may be budgets.

00:34:59.520 --> 00:35:01.609
It may be populations.

00:35:01.609 --> 00:35:04.150
It's stuff that when you hear
something on the news, you say,

00:35:04.150 --> 00:35:05.040
hold on a minute.

00:35:05.040 --> 00:35:06.960
That's not a big number,
because it compares

00:35:06.960 --> 00:35:09.937
with that number in this way.

00:35:09.937 --> 00:35:11.520
And that's one of
the techniques here.

00:35:19.134 --> 00:35:21.050
AUDIENCE: You were saying
that on your website

00:35:21.050 --> 00:35:23.865
you have like a database
of numbers you compare to.

00:35:23.865 --> 00:35:24.740
ANDREW ELLIOTT: Yeah.

00:35:24.740 --> 00:35:27.040
AUDIENCE: Can you tell
us what some of them are?

00:35:27.040 --> 00:35:29.607
I assume one is the 40,000.

00:35:29.607 --> 00:35:30.440
ANDREW ELLIOTT: Yes.

00:35:30.440 --> 00:35:32.439
Well, they come from all
sorts of things really.

00:35:32.439 --> 00:35:35.630
I mean, what I tried to do
is to find numbers that would

00:35:35.630 --> 00:35:37.250
make meaningful comparisons.

00:35:37.250 --> 00:35:43.730
So some of them are just routine
household or everyday objects,

00:35:43.730 --> 00:35:46.160
like the size of a Post-it note.

00:35:46.160 --> 00:35:49.204
Some of them are
things like landmarks,

00:35:49.204 --> 00:35:50.870
the height of the
Empire State Building,

00:35:50.870 --> 00:35:57.050
or the height of the Eiffel
Tower, or something like that.

00:35:57.050 --> 00:36:00.020
And one of the things that is
on the website and in the book

00:36:00.020 --> 00:36:02.960
is I try and find pairs
of those numbers that

00:36:02.960 --> 00:36:05.120
compare in an interesting way.

00:36:05.120 --> 00:36:09.420
So for example, the Empire State
Building is 5,000 Post-it notes

00:36:09.420 --> 00:36:11.970
high almost exactly.

00:36:11.970 --> 00:36:15.110
I do the comparison
to within 2%.

00:36:15.110 --> 00:36:17.810
And you get some really
interesting numbers

00:36:17.810 --> 00:36:18.720
that come through.

00:36:18.720 --> 00:36:20.990
And this has an
interesting function,

00:36:20.990 --> 00:36:24.570
because it makes you think
about the numbers themselves.

00:36:24.570 --> 00:36:26.100
But it's almost like a triangle.

00:36:26.100 --> 00:36:27.120
Here's the Empire
State Building.

00:36:27.120 --> 00:36:28.190
Here's a Post-it note.

00:36:28.190 --> 00:36:29.656
And here's the number 5,000.

00:36:29.656 --> 00:36:31.280
And it gives you a
little bit of a feel

00:36:31.280 --> 00:36:33.390
for each of those
points of the triangle

00:36:33.390 --> 00:36:35.450
when you think about them
in that relationship.

00:36:35.450 --> 00:36:37.940
Of course, it means
nothing in terms

00:36:37.940 --> 00:36:40.930
of if there is a
conspiracy theory here

00:36:40.930 --> 00:36:44.070
that they've designed it
to fit the Post-it note,

00:36:44.070 --> 00:36:47.210
but it's still something
that sticks in the mind.

00:36:47.210 --> 00:36:50.000
And that's an interesting
way of going about it.

00:36:50.000 --> 00:36:52.460
But, yes, the numbers
on the website

00:36:52.460 --> 00:36:57.140
are things like the length of
the Nile River, the population

00:36:57.140 --> 00:36:58.639
of Brazil.

00:36:58.639 --> 00:37:00.680
There are numbers that
you can compare things to.

00:37:05.400 --> 00:37:09.469
That may or may not be
intriguing when you see them.

