Second half of the book firstly
gets into certain numbers

00:37:52.760 --> 00:37:53.320
from science.

00:37:53.320 --> 00:37:55.880
So we talk about how
you can visualize

00:37:55.880 --> 00:37:58.730
or start to grasp,
for example, the size

00:37:58.730 --> 00:37:59.930
of the observable universe.

00:37:59.930 --> 00:38:03.060
You know, get there by stages.

00:38:03.060 --> 00:38:06.020
And there's a chapter
on information.

00:38:06.020 --> 00:38:08.880
And we go into things like
how do you measure information

00:38:08.880 --> 00:38:12.650
at all, how much information
is contained in the text, how

00:38:12.650 --> 00:38:14.836
much information is stored
in physical devices,

00:38:14.836 --> 00:38:15.710
and things like that.

00:38:15.710 --> 00:38:17.870
Of course, that part of
the book is out of date

00:38:17.870 --> 00:38:20.600
before it's published.

00:38:20.600 --> 00:38:24.110
But nonetheless, in the sense
that the principles remain.

00:38:24.110 --> 00:38:27.272
And then there's a chapter on
mathematical numbers as well.

00:38:27.272 --> 00:38:28.730
It's really not a
book about maths,

00:38:28.730 --> 00:38:33.020
but we have to touch on things
like explain that infinity

00:38:33.020 --> 00:38:35.870
is not actually a number
on the number line,

00:38:35.870 --> 00:38:37.730
or you'll talk about
Graham's number, which

00:38:37.730 --> 00:38:40.640
is an interesting-- you
know Graham's number?

00:38:40.640 --> 00:38:41.450
AUDIENCE: The name.

00:38:41.450 --> 00:38:42.324
ANDREW ELLIOTT: Yeah.

00:38:42.324 --> 00:38:44.330
I mean, it's a number.

00:38:44.330 --> 00:38:46.640
I first came across it
when it was in the Guinness

00:38:46.640 --> 00:38:49.880
Book of Records as the
largest number ever used

00:38:49.880 --> 00:38:52.240
in a serious
mathematical context.

00:38:52.240 --> 00:38:52.740
OK.

00:38:52.740 --> 00:38:55.520
So Graham's number
is just a recipe

00:38:55.520 --> 00:38:58.400
for taking powers of numbers
an unbelievably large number

00:38:58.400 --> 00:38:59.750
of times.

00:38:59.750 --> 00:39:01.730
You could not write
down Graham's number.

00:39:01.730 --> 00:39:05.180
The universe would
not have space for it.

00:39:05.180 --> 00:39:08.600
So the question is, is it even
a number if all that it is

00:39:08.600 --> 00:39:12.340
is an algorithm for
doing computation

00:39:12.340 --> 00:39:15.170
that you could never carry out.

00:39:15.170 --> 00:39:19.530
But actually even if
I go and buy a coffee,

00:39:19.530 --> 00:39:22.760
and it cost me two pounds
50, that number two pounds

00:39:22.760 --> 00:39:25.260
50 is just an algorithm.

00:39:25.260 --> 00:39:26.690
It's not the number itself.

00:39:26.690 --> 00:39:28.119
There are some digits there.

00:39:28.119 --> 00:39:29.660
And we, our heads,
have the algorithm

00:39:29.660 --> 00:39:31.290
for turning that into a number.

00:39:31.290 --> 00:39:35.060
So there's no point of principle
difference between the two.

00:39:35.060 --> 00:39:37.320
AUDIENCE: Thank
you for the talk.

00:39:37.320 --> 00:39:40.730
I have a question,
because, I mean, my family,

00:39:40.730 --> 00:39:44.720
like half of the kids don't
understand math, you know.

00:39:44.720 --> 00:39:46.820
I was fortunate to
understand it a bit.

00:39:46.820 --> 00:39:50.180
But do you think this
like understanding

00:39:50.180 --> 00:39:53.030
numbers should have a
bigger role in school,

00:39:53.030 --> 00:39:55.200
because how math is
taught in Germany,

00:39:55.200 --> 00:40:00.410
for instance, is still very
basic and very on the numbers,

00:40:00.410 --> 00:40:02.540
rather than on what
the numbers mean.

00:40:02.540 --> 00:40:04.915
ANDREW ELLIOTT: I think that's
an interesting thing here,

00:40:04.915 --> 00:40:08.430
because I think maths
is a thing of beauty.

00:40:08.430 --> 00:40:12.560
Math is an abstract
thinking skill

00:40:12.560 --> 00:40:15.770
of subtlety and profundity.

00:40:15.770 --> 00:40:18.710
And what we call--

00:40:18.710 --> 00:40:23.050
I mean what I call numeracy,
of course it touches on maths,

00:40:23.050 --> 00:40:23.907
but it is not maths.

00:40:23.907 --> 00:40:24.990
It's dealing with numbers.

00:40:24.990 --> 00:40:27.070
It's the way in which
those abstractions of maths

00:40:27.070 --> 00:40:28.540
connect to the real world.

00:40:28.540 --> 00:40:29.550
Yeah.

00:40:29.550 --> 00:40:30.700
And I think--

00:40:30.700 --> 00:40:31.670
I mean, I'm no teacher.

00:40:31.670 --> 00:40:32.770
I'm no educational expert.

00:40:32.770 --> 00:40:34.750
I can't speak with
authority on those matters.

00:40:34.750 --> 00:40:40.890
But it seems to me that we
leave behind numbers too soon

00:40:40.890 --> 00:40:42.550
and move on to maths.

00:40:42.550 --> 00:40:44.320
And I think that some
of the things I've

00:40:44.320 --> 00:40:46.600
been looking at
here suggest to me

00:40:46.600 --> 00:40:50.620
that there's much more that we
can do in terms of what I would

00:40:50.620 --> 00:40:54.400
call adult numeracy
or advanced numeracy

00:40:54.400 --> 00:40:56.500
to actually think about
numbers into the millions

00:40:56.500 --> 00:40:59.950
and billions and trillions.

00:40:59.950 --> 00:41:04.300
And there's a shift that
happens, I mean we all,

00:41:04.300 --> 00:41:06.790
when we start thinking--

00:41:06.790 --> 00:41:10.210
in junior school, we're thinking
in terms of linear numbers,

00:41:10.210 --> 00:41:12.479
in linear scales.

00:41:12.479 --> 00:41:14.020
But truthfully, the
interesting stuff

00:41:14.020 --> 00:41:16.180
happens when you
start looking at more

00:41:16.180 --> 00:41:18.250
like logarithmic
scales, when you start

00:41:18.250 --> 00:41:22.040
thinking of things in terms
of multiples of each other,

00:41:22.040 --> 00:41:23.592
and when you--

00:41:23.592 --> 00:41:26.050
the way to understand things
like the size of the universe,

00:41:26.050 --> 00:41:27.466
you can't do it
if you're thinking

00:41:27.466 --> 00:41:28.660
in terms of a linear scale.

00:41:28.660 --> 00:41:31.570
You've got to think in terms
of orders of magnitude in terms

00:41:31.570 --> 00:41:33.100
of powers and so on.

00:41:33.100 --> 00:41:37.180
And I think that that
numerate thinking--

00:41:37.180 --> 00:41:40.970
I'm not aware that that's much
part of school mathematics.

00:41:40.970 --> 00:41:42.700
And I think it's
actually very important.

00:41:42.700 --> 00:41:47.500
And it's very useful to
think in terms of proportions

00:41:47.500 --> 00:41:49.990
rather than linear scales.

00:41:49.990 --> 00:41:52.252
SPEAKER 1: Thank you
again, Andrew Elliott.

00:41:52.252 --> 00:41:54.040
ANDREW ELLIOTT: Thank you.

00:41:54.040 --> 00:41:56.530
Thank you all for
your attention.

